\ls5\adjustright \fs26\lang2057\cgrid {\fs24 GLEESON CJ, GAUDRON, McHUGH, GUMMOW, HAYNE AND CALLINAN JJ}{.   The Full Court has before it questions concerning the construction and validity of certain pr
ovisions of what generally is identified as the national scheme for corporate regulation.  This replaced the previous co\_
operative scheme and was established pursuant to heads of agreement formulated at a meeting of representatives of the Executive Governm
ents of the Commonwealth, the States and the Northern Territory at Alice Springs in June 1990 ("the Alice Springs Agreement")}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar
\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab The parties to the Alice Springs Agreement are now parties to an agreement styled }{\i Corporations Agreement}{ made on 23\~
September 1997.  Clause 1006 thereof provides for the former agreement to cease to have effect.}}}{.  The national scheme was implemented by legislation of the legislatures of all the polities that were parties to the Alice Springs Agreement}{
\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab 
The origins and structure of the national scheme are further outlined in }{\i Gould v Brown}{ (1998) 193 CLR 346 at 393\_394, 413\_415, 433\_437.}}}{
.  In construing that legislation, regard may be had to the Alice Springs Agreement as part of the relevant context}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar
\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab }{\i CIC Insurance Ltd v Bankstown Football Club Ltd}{ (1997) 187 CLR 384 at 408.}}}{.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s27 \fs20\cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2\tab}}\pard \s27\qj\fi-567\li567\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx567\tx1134\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls5\pnrnot0\pndec\pnfs20\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang}\ls5\adjustright 
{\tab This case concerns the provisions of legislation of the Commonwealth and Western Australia respecting the institution and conduct of prosecutions under the national scheme.  The decisions of this Court in }{\i Byrnes v The Queen}{\cs21\b\super 
\chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab (1999) 73 ALJR 1292; 164 ALR 520.}}}{
 and }{\i Bond v The Queen}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ 
\tab (2000) 74 ALJR 597; 169 ALR 607.}}}{ are not determinative of the issues now arising.  The earlier cases concerned the competency of appeals by the prosecution against sentences imposed upon conviction for offences under the co\_
operative scheme, not the national scheme.
\par }\pard\plain \s30\qj\li567\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\keepn\widctlpar\tx567\tx1134\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright \fs26\ul\lang2057\cgrid {The issues
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s27 \fs20\cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 3\tab}}\pard\plain \s27\qj\fi-567\li567\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx567\tx1134\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls5\pnrnot0\pndec\pnfs20\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang}
\ls5\adjustright \fs26\lang2057\cgrid {\tab By indictment dated 15\~July 1997 and presented to the District Court of Western Australia, Craig Allan Hughes ("the accused"), with Noel Andrew
 Bell, is prosecuted on three counts of making available at Perth, between 1\~February 1992 and 24\~November 1994, "prescribed interests" contrary to s\~1064(1) of the Corporations Law ("the Law") read with s\~
1311(1)(a) of the Law.  The indictment opens with the words:
\par }\pard\plain \s28\qj\li1134\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright \fs26\lang3081\cgrid {
"The Commonwealth Director of Public Prosecutions ['the DPP'] who prosecutes in this behalf for Her Majesty the Queen \'85"
\par }\pard\plain \s27\qj\li567\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx567\tx1134\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright \fs26\lang2057\cgrid {and is signed:
\par }\pard\plain \s28\qj\li1134\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright \fs26\lang3081\cgrid {"IAN RUSSELL BERMINGHAM
\par for and on behalf of the Commonwealth
\par Director of Public Prosecutions".
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s27\qj\li567\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx567\tx1134\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright \fs26\lang2057\cgrid {The DPP holds an office established by s\~5(2) of the }{\i 
Director of Public Prosecutions Act}{ 1983 (Cth) ("the DPP Act").  Section\~6 details various functions of the DPP and s\~9 confers various powers to be exercised for the purpose of the performance of those functions.  
One of the functions of the DPP is to institute and carry on prosecutions on indictment for indictable offences against the laws of the Commonwealth (s\~
6(1)(a), (b)).  However, the DPP contends that, by reason of other provisions in the DPP Act and of the 
operation of other Commonwealth and State laws, in the present case he is prosecuting for offences against the laws of Western Australia.  It will be necessary to determine whether this is so and, if so, whether the DPP is competent to act in that fashion
.  The accused denies that competence.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s27 \fs20\cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 4\tab}}\pard \s27\qj\fi-567\li567\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx567\tx1134\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls5\pnrnot0\pndec\pnfs20\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang}\ls5\adjustright 
{\tab On 8\~August 1997, the accused and Mr Bell were arraigned and pleaded not guilty.  On 23\~August 1999 the accused applied to the District Court on motion to quash the indictment.  Thereafter, this Court ordered the removal under s\~40 of the }{\i 
Judiciary Act}{ 1903 (Cth) ("the Judiciary Act") of so much of the cause pending in the District Court as is involved in the motion to quash the indictment.  The parties then agreed certain facts for the purposes of the proceeding in th
e High Court and there is now before the Full Court, pursuant to an order made by a Justice under s\~18 of the Judiciary Act, a number of questions for determination.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s27 \fs20\cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 5\tab}}\pard \s27\qj\fi-567\li567\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx567\tx1134\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls5\pnrnot0\pndec\pnfs20\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang}\ls5\adjustright 
{\tab As indicated above, the accused submits that there is lacking the necessary legislative a
uthority under Commonwealth and State law for the DPP to prosecute the offences specified in the indictment.  It is also asserted that the relevant State and Commonwealth legislation is not effective to render the accused liable to any prosecution for the
 offences alleged.  In particular, the accused contends that the effect of the State legislation is to render offences against State law offences against Commonwealth law.  Such a transmutation is said to be beyond the competence of the State legislature.

\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s27 \fs20\cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 6\tab}}\pard \s27\qj\fi-567\li567\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx567\tx1134\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls5\pnrnot0\pndec\pnfs20\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang}\ls5\adjustright 
{\tab The reference already made to "the Law" is to the Corporations Law set out in s\~82 of the }{\i Corporations Act}{ 1989 (Cth) ("the Corporations Act").  Section\~7 of the }{\i Corporations (Western Australia) Act}{
 1990 (WA) ("the WA Corporations Act") provides:
\par }\pard\plain \s28\qj\li1134\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright \fs26\lang3081\cgrid {\tab "The Cor
porations Law set out in section 82 of the Corporations Act as in force for the time being \endash 
\par }\pard \s28\qj\li1134\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx1440\tx1985\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\tab (a)\tab applies as a law of Western Australia; and
