\ls5\adjustright {\tab It is helpful, in my view, in construing the provisions of the federal and State legislation which the accused challenges to view that legislation in the context of the purpose
s for which it was enacted.  For most of the first century of federation the regulation of corporations in Australia was substantially left to State and Territory law.  Because of the paucity of relevant federal courts, jurisdiction over corporations was 
s
ubstantially confined to that of State and Territory courts, save for a relatively small number of cases which found their way to this Court or to the Privy Council.  The growth of the national and global economies and of a significant number of corporati
o
ns operating in several or all of the jurisdictions of Australia (and overseas) eventually produced the first cooperative scheme for corporate regulation.  This involved generally identical Companies Codes and an interjurisdictional mechanism designed to 
develop and maintain uniform administration and legislative amendments}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ 
\tab The history is found in }{\i The Broken Hill Pty Co Ltd \~v National Companies and Securities Commission }{(1986) 160 CLR 492 at 505-509.  See also Ford, Austin and Ramsay, }{\i Ford's Principles of Corporations Law}{
, 9th ed (1999) at 45-47; Saunders, "Administrative Law and Relations Between Governments:  Australia and Europe Compared", unpublished paper (2000) at 23-25.}}}{.  
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s27 \fs20\cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 56\tab}}\pard \s27\qj\fi-567\li567\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx567\tx1134\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls5\pnrnot0\pndec\pnfs20\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang}
\ls5\adjustright {\page \tab The inadequacies and inefficiencies of this cooperative arrangement soon became apparent.  Meanwhile, a number of decisions of this Court}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0
\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab Especially }{\i Strickland\~v Rocla Concrete Pipes Ltd }{(1971) 124 CLR 468; }{\i State Superannuation Board v Trade Practices Commission }{
(1982) 150 CLR 282; }{\i Fencott v Muller }{(1983) 152 CLR 570.}}}{, disapproving of and discarding earlier authority}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar
\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab }{\i Huddart, Parker & Co Pty Ltd v Moorehead }{(1909) 8 CLR 330.}}}{, attracted fresh attention to the potential of the corporations power under the Constitution}
{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab Constitution, s 51(xx).}}}{
 to afford a substantial foundation for federal regulation of corporations of the kind described in the Constitution}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar
\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab Namely, foreign corporations and trading or financial corporations.}}}{.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s27 \fs20\cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 57\tab}}\pard \s27\qj\fi-567\li567\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx567\tx1134\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls5\pnrnot0\pndec\pnfs20\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang}
\ls5\adjustright {\tab It was the pursuit of this new id
ea, together with the need for a more efficient system of national regulation of corporations in Australia, that led to the enactment of the Corporations Act.  That Act was not proclaimed to commence pending a determination by this Court of questions rela
t
ing to the validity of a number of its provisions.  Those provisions were "based upon the assumption that the Commonwealth has power to legislate for the incorporation of a company if the subscribers to the memorandum of association intend that trading or
 financial activities are to be a substantial part of its activities"}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ 
\tab }{\i New South Wales v The Commonwealth}{ (}{\i The Incorporation Case}{) (1990) 169 CLR 482 at 496.}}}{
.  Furthermore the Corporations Act, as originally enacted, assumed "that the Commonwealth can prohibit the incorporation of a company under the law of a State or Territory if the body upon incorporation will be a trading or financial corporation"}{
\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab }{\i Incorporation Case }{(1990) 169 CLR 482 at 496.}}}{.  
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s27 \fs20\cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 58\tab}}\pard \s27\qj\fi-567\li567\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx567\tx1134\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls5\pnrnot0\pndec\pnfs20\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang}
\ls5\adjustright {\tab In the }{\i Incorporation Case}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab 
(1990) 169 CLR 482.}}}{ this Court, by majority}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab 
Mason CJ, Brennan, Dawson, Toohey, Gaudron and McHugh\~JJ; Deane\~J dissenting.}}}{, held that the corporations power did not entitle the Federal Parliament to legislate for the incorporation of trading and financial corpo
rations.  A key assumption of the Corporations Act, as enacted, was thus invalidated.  This narrow decision of the Court will, in my opinion, one day need to be revisited}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain 
\s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab cf }{\i Byrnes }{(1999) 73 ALJR 1292 at 1308; 164 ALR 520 at 543.}}}{
.  A factual consequence has been the grotesque complications that exist in the regulation of corporations under Australian law illustrated in }{\i Byrnes}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar
\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab (1999) 73 ALJR 1292; 164 ALR 520.}}}{, }{\i Bond}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar
\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab (2000) 74 ALJR 597; 169 ALR 607.}}}{ and now this case.  
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s27 \fs20\cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 59\tab}}\pard \s27\qj\fi-567\li567\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx567\tx1134\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls5\pnrnot0\pndec\pnfs20\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang}
\ls5\adjustright {\tab The precise reasons for adopting the scheme that now comes under scrutiny, in response to the }{\i Incorporation Case}{, are not disclosed.  The rejection of a formal a
mendment of the Constitution to allow ample legislative powers to the Federal Parliament can doubtless be explained by the discouraging history of referendum proposals under s\~128 of the Constitution}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain 
\s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab 
A number of proposals have been made for the amendment of the Constitution to enlarge the powers of the Federal Parliament over trade and commerce and corporations.  Such proposals were put an
d failed to pass in April 1911, May 1913 and December 1919.  See Blackshield and Williams, }{\i Australian Constitutional Law and Theory}{, 2nd ed (1998) at 1184-1185.}}}{.  The disinclination to refer powers to}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote 
\pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab Under the Constitution, s 51(xxxvii).}}}{, or to request
 and concur in the exercise of State powers by}{\cs21\b\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s20\qj\fi-454\li1021\sa240\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx510\tx1021\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\cs21\b\fs22 \chftn }{ \tab 
Under the Constitution, s 51(xxxviii).}}}{, the Federal Parliament is said to arise out of a concern that such powers, once surrendered, might not be capable of retrieval by the States.  But only political considerations, disputes over revenue and pos
sibly a feeling of discouragement following the }{\i Incorporation Case}{ can explain the nearly incomprehensible scheme of legislation eventually adopted.  
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\s27 \fs20\cgrid \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 60\tab}}\pard \s27\qj\fi-567\li567\sa280\sl-280\slmult0\widctlpar\tx567\tx1134\tx1559\tx2126\tx2693{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls5\pnrnot0\pndec\pnfs20\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang}
\ls5\adjustright {\tab Courts, including this Court, regularly speak in terms of the "intention" of the legislature when interp
reting particular legislation.  This polite but unacceptable fiction has never been shown in starker relief than in the present case.  So complex is the interlocking legislation, with fiction piled upon fiction, that it must be doubted whether any of thos
e
 presenting and enacting it were truly aware of precisely what they were doing.  It may be hoped that this and other recent decisions, together with the great national importance of the subject matter of the legislation, will encourage its early reconside
ration and the adoption of a simpler constitutional foundation to reduce the perils that are otherwise bound to recur, possibly with serious results.
